article.description: Cheryl Ford scored 22 points and had a season-high 19 rebounds to help the Shock beat the Silver Stars 63-59.
article.headline: Ford's double-double leads Shock past Silver Stars
article.linkText: Ford's double-double leads Shock past Silver Stars
article.story:
SAN ANTONIO (AP) -- The San Antonio Silver Stars had no one to stop Cheryl Ford. Ford scored 22 points and had a season-high 19 rebounds to help the Shock beat the Silver Stars 63-59 Tuesday night. "What else can you say?," Shock coach Bill Laimbeer said. "Cheryl was a monster tonight. She completely dominated the game." It was the league-leading ninth double-double for Ford this season. That's one more than Lisa Leslie, who scored a career-high 41 points against San Antonio on Sunday while leading Los Angeles to its eighth straight victory. Ford has had two 18-rebound games this season, and her effort helped the Shock (10-4) stay a half-game behind Connecticut for the lead in the Eastern Conference. Detroit has won six straight games. The Sun defeated Houston 73-57 on Tuesday. San Antonio (6-8) trailed by one point with 18 seconds left, but Agnieszka Bibrzycka and Shanna Zolman missed 3-point attempts before Deanna Nolan got loose for a layup and free throw on a foul by Bibrzycka with 5 seconds left. "I thought we defended well on everyone else, but [Ford] was the one we couldn't finish the play on," San Antonio coach Dan Hughes said. "She can finish over the top of our defenders. Her rebounding is just the best in the league." The Silver Stars have lost four straight games. Sophia Young scored 16 points and Bibrzycka added 15. Zolman had 12. The Shock were plagued by a pair of horrid shooting stretches. Detroit missed 11 consecutive shots to end the first quarter and also went 1-for-10 to start the third quarter. "It was an ugly one," Laimbeer said. "But we'll take it." The Shock overcame the first-half shooting problems. Detroit led by as much as 10 points in the second quarter behind 12 first-half rebounds from Ford. "We knew we were going to have to pound the ball inside tonight," Ford said. "Our game plan was to go inside, rebound and limit our turnovers." But San Antonio made it a game following Detroit's slow shooting start after halftime. The Silver Stars went ahead 34-33 with 4:08 to go in the third quarter on Young's layup. Swin Cash added 13 points for the Shock and Plenette Pierson had 10.

Game notes
Silver Stars reserve forward La Toya Thomas, the No. 1 pick in the 2003 draft, missed her first game after suffering a lateral meniscus tendon tear in her left knee in Sunday's 105-80 loss at Los Angeles. Thomas, still on the active list but wearing street clothes Tuesday, was averaging nine points and five rebounds per game. Ford had 12 rebounds in the first half, which tied a franchise record. She missed the single-game record of 22, which she set during the 2004 season at San Antonio.
